issue.title: Refactor get_uuid functionality to use required dependency injection
issue.body:
This PR refactors the `get_uuid` functionality in `RealOverlayController` to use required dependency injection, making the code more testable and moving towards eliminating the need for separate controller implementations.

## Changes Made

### RealOverlayController
- Added required `get_uuid` parameter to constructor that must be provided by the caller
- Modified `get_uuid()` method to delegate to the injected function while preserving all existing error handling and state management (e.g., `missing_local_issuer_certificate`)
- Removed dependency on importing `mojang.get_uuid` directly in the controller

### Main Module
- Updated `__main__.py` to import `get_uuid` from `prism.mojang` and pass it explicitly to `RealOverlayController`
- Maintains the same behavior as before but with explicit dependency declaration

### Tests
- Updated all test files to pass the `get_uuid` function explicitly to both controller types
- Added comprehensive tests demonstrating the dependency injection functionality
- All existing functionality preserved and tested

## Benefits

1. **Explicit dependencies**: The `get_uuid` function must now be explicitly provided, making dependencies clear
2. **Better testability**: Tests can inject custom `get_uuid` functions without relying on monkey-patching
3. **Consistent interface**: Dependencies are explicitly declared in constructors
4. **Preserved functionality**: All error handling, caching, and state management remains unchanged

## Example Usage

```python
from prism.mojang import get_uuid
from prism.overlay.real_controller import RealOverlayController

# Standard usage with real get_uuid function
controller = RealOverlayController(
    state=state,
    settings=settings, 
    nick_database=nick_db,
    get_uuid=get_uuid  # Required dependency
)

# Testing with mock function
def mock_get_uuid(username: str) -> str:
    return f"test-uuid-{username}"

test_controller = RealOverlayController(
    state=state,
    settings=settings,
    nick_database=nick_db,
    get_uuid=mock_get_uuid  # Injected test dependency
)
```

This change establishes a foundation for cleaner dependency management and makes the transition toward unified controller implementations more straightforward.

Changelog

Sourced from react-router's changelog.

7.8.1

Patch Changes

  • Fix usage of optional path segments in nested routes defined using absolute paths (#14135)
  • Bubble client pre-next middleware error to the shallowest ancestor that needs to load, not strictly the shallowest ancestor with a loader (#14150)
  • Fix optional static segment matching in matchPath (#11813)
  • Fix prerendering when a basename is set with ssr:false (#13791)
  • Provide isRouteErrorResponse utility in react-server environments (#14166)
  • Propagate non-redirect Responses thrown from middleware to the error boundary on document/data requests (#14182)
  • Handle meta and links Route Exports in RSC Data Mode (#14136)
  • Properly convert returned/thrown data() values to Response instances via Response.json() in resource routes and middleware (#14159, #14181)

7.8.0

Minor Changes

  • Add nonce prop to Links & PrefetchPageLinks (#14048)
  • Add loaderData arguments/properties alongside existing data arguments/properties to provide consistency and clarity between loaderData and actionData across the board (#14047)
    • Updated types: Route.MetaArgs, Route.MetaMatch, MetaArgs, MetaMatch, Route.ComponentProps.matches, UIMatch
    • @deprecated warnings have been added to the existing data properties to point users to new loaderData properties, in preparation for removing the data properties in a future major release

Patch Changes

  • Prevent "Did not find corresponding fetcher result" console error when navigating during a fetcher.submit revalidation (#14114)

  • Bubble client-side middleware errors prior to next to the appropriate ancestor error boundary (#14138)

  • Switch Lazy Route Discovery manifest URL generation to usea standalone URLSearchParams instance instead of URL.searchParams to avoid a major performance bottleneck in Chrome (#14084)

  • Adjust internal RSC usage of React.use to avoid Webpack compilation errors when using React 18 (#14113)

  • Remove dependency on @types/node in TypeScript declaration files (#14059)

  • Fix types for UIMatch to reflect that the loaderData/data properties may be undefined (#12206)

    • When an ErrorBoundary is being rendered, not all active matches will have loader data available, since it may have been their loader that threw to trigger the boundary
    • The UIMatch.data type was not correctly handing this and would always reflect the presence of data, leading to the unexpected runtime errors when an ErrorBoundary was rendered
    • ‚ö†Ô∏è This may cause some type errors to show up in your code for unguarded match.data accesses - you should properly guard for undefined values in those scenarios.

export function loader() {

}

let matches = useMatches();
let rootMatch = matches[0] as UIMatch<Awaited<ReturnType<typeof loader>>>;
//  ^ rootMatch.data is incorrectly typed here, so TypeScript does not

Hi there! üëã

I‚Äôm a master‚Äôs student researching **cost considerations in cloud infrastructure**. As part of this project, we ran a static analysis tool (linter) on your repository to identify cost-related misconfigurations.

We found **5 potential issues** across **4 files**, some of which might **significantly affect the cloud costs** of your project.

Are you interested in the **linter results**? Reply here. We‚Äôll send **the report along with a short follow-up survey** (~5 min) to evaluate our tool and better understand cost considerations in open-source projects for our research. All data will be treated confidentially.

If you‚Äôre curious about our work, we are investigating how developers approach cost in cloud infrastructure, specifically Terraform and AWS CloudFormation. Our goal is to identify **patterns and anti-patterns** to help developers make **more cost-aware infrastructure decisions**. You can check out what we‚Äôve discovered so far here: [https://search-rug.github.io/iac-cost-patterns/](https://search-rug.github.io/iac-cost-patterns/). If you have any questions or would like to discuss our research, don‚Äôt hesitate to reach out!

Thank you for your time and support! ü§ó

issue.title: Exercise: Secure your Repository's Supply Chain
issue.body: ## Secure your Repository's Supply Chain üëã Hey there @24127031-Jishnu! Welcome to your Skills exercise! Let's explore how to secure your repository's supply chain, understand dependencies in your environment, and find vulnerabilities in those dependencies and patch them. üíª‚ú® --- ‚ú® **This is an interactive, hands-on GitHub Skills exercise!** As you complete each step, I‚Äôll leave updates in the comments: - ‚úÖ Check your work and guide you forward - üí° Share helpful tips and resources - üöÄ Celebrate your progress and completion Let‚Äôs get started - good luck and have fun! ‚Äî Mona

comment.body:
## Step 1: Review and add dependencies using dependency graph

**What's the big deal about securing your repository's supply chain?**: With the accelerated use of open source, most projects depend on hundreds of open-source dependencies. This poses a security problem: what if the dependencies you're using are vulnerable? You could be putting your users at risk of a supply chain attack. One of the most important things you can do to protect your supply chain is to patch your vulnerable dependencies and replace any malware.

GitHub offers a range of features to help you understand the dependencies in your environment, know about vulnerabilities in those dependencies, and patch them. The supply chain features on GitHub are:

- Dependency graph
- Dependency review
- Dependabot alerts
- Dependabot updates
  - Dependabot security updates
  - Dependabot version updates

**What is a dependency graph**: The dependency graph is a summary of the manifest and lock files stored in a repository and any dependencies that are submitted for the repository using the dependency submission API (beta). For each repository, it shows:

- Dependencies, the ecosystems and packages it depends on
- Dependents, the repositories and packages that depend on it

### :keyboard: Activity 1.1: Verify that dependency graph is enabled

**We recommend opening another browser tab to work through the following activities so you can keep these instructions open for reference.**

>[!NOTE]
> Dependency graph is enabled by default for all new public repositories.

1. Navigate to the **Settings** tab.
1. Click **Advanced Security**.
1. Verify **Dependency Graph** is **Enabled**

### :keyboard: Activity 1.2: Add a new dependency and view your dependency graph

1. Navigate to the **Code** tab and locate the `code/src/AttendeeSite` folder.
1. Commit the following content on the `main` branch to the `package-lock.json` file as the last item on the `dependencies` map _(after the third to last bracket `}` and before the last two brackets)_

    > ü™ß **Note:** You can edit and commit the file on github.com directly or hit the `.` key to open the lightweight editor to edit and commit changes.

    ```json
    ,
    "follow-redirects": {
      "version": "1.14.1",
      "resolved": "https://registry.npmjs.org/follow-redirects/-/follow-redirects-1.14.1.tgz",
      "integrity": "sha512-HWqDgT7ZEkqRzBvc2s64vSZ/hfOceEol3ac/7tKwzuvEyWx3/4UegXh5oBOIotkGsObyk3xznnSRVADBgWSQVg=="
    }
    ```

1. Navigate to the **Insights** tab.
1. Select **Dependency graph** from the side navigation bar.
1. Review all the dependencies on the **Dependencies** tab.
1. Search for `follow-redirects` and review the new dependency you just added.
   ![Screen Shot showing the "follow-redirects" dependency.](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6351798/196288729-734e3319-c5d7-4f35-a19c-676c12f0e27d.png)
1. With the new dependency added, Mona should already be busy checking your work. Give her a moment and keep watch in the comments. You will see her respond with progress info and the next lesson.

issue.body:
# üìö Comprehensive Workflow Documentation & Enterprise Footer Tracking

## Enhanced Documentation Coverage

### üß™ Smart Testing Strategy Documentation
- **Local vs CI Strategy**: Fast local tests (< 2 min) + comprehensive CI tests leveraging unlimited GitHub Actions minutes
- **Cross-Platform Testing**: ARM64 (local) vs AMD64 (CI) compatibility guidelines
- **Performance Testing**: Visual regression matrix (20 combinations), accessibility audits, performance monitoring
- **Command Reference**: Complete testing command documentation with timeouts and strategies

### üîí Security Scanning & Troubleshooting
- **TruffleHog Configuration**: Fixed BASE/HEAD commit issues for main branch workflows
- **Context-Aware Scanning**: Differential (PR), single-commit (main), full-repository (scheduled) modes
- **Security Troubleshooting**: Comprehensive guide for common GitHub Actions security scanning issues
- **Vulnerability Management**: Complete workflow troubleshooting reference

### üèóÔ∏è CI/CD Pipeline Architecture Documentation
- **Three-Tier Deployment**: PR Preview ‚Üí Netlify Staging ‚Üí GitHub Pages Production
- **Workflow Resilience**: Exponential backoff, circuit breaker patterns, comprehensive error handling
- **Environment Management**: Clear separation and naming for AI and human understanding
- **Version Management**: Release-please integration and semantic versioning documentation

## Enterprise-Grade Footer Version Tracking

### üåê Cross-Environment Correlation System
- **Environment Detection**: Production, Staging, Preview, Development with automatic URL-based detection
- **Build Metadata**: Version, commit SHA, build number, timestamps with GitHub Actions integration
- **Repository Correlation**: Direct links to releases, commits, PRs, and deployment workflows
- **Release Tracking**: Commits ahead counter, last release tag, compare URLs for change tracking

### üìä Version Display Features
- **Environment Badges**: Color-coded visual indicators (Production: green, Staging: yellow, etc.)
- **Clickable Links**: All version elements link to relevant GitHub resources
- **Context-Aware Display**: Different information based on deployment environment
- **Mobile Responsive**: Professional display across all device types

### üîó Cross-Deployment Navigation
- **Release Notes**: Direct links to GitHub releases for production versions
- **PR Context**: For preview deployments, shows PR number and branch information
- **Staging Context**: Build metadata and deployment workflow links
- **Development Context**: Local development server and file modification tracking

## Technical Implementation

### üìÅ File Changes
- **CLAUDE.md**: 400+ lines of comprehensive documentation covering all workflow aspects
- **template.html**: Enterprise footer with sophisticated environment detection JavaScript
- **.claude/settings.local.json**: Enhanced configuration for better AI assistant integration

### üéØ User Experience Benefits
- **Instant Environment Identification**: Clear visual indicators of which environment you're viewing
- **One-Click Navigation**: Jump between environments, releases, and repository resources
- **Build Traceability**: Track any deployment back to its source commit and workflow run
- **Release Correlation**: Understand exactly which version is deployed where

### üöÄ Performance Impact
- **Zero Build Impact**: Footer JavaScript loads asynchronously without blocking page rendering
- **Optimized Asset Loading**: Version information cached and loaded efficiently
- **Mobile Performance**: Responsive design with minimal bandwidth usage
- **Cross-Browser Compatibility**: Works across all modern browsers and devices

## Addresses User Requirements

‚úÖ **Smart Testing Strategy**: "run long tests on CI and basically for functionally local"
‚úÖ **Unlimited GitHub Minutes**: "since this is a open repo github gives us unlimited minutes"
‚úÖ **AI Context**: "make sure everything its explicit and with context so AI can always understand"
‚úÖ **Enterprise Footer**: "on footer of site is easy to cross check this with useful links"
‚úÖ **Environment Tracking**: "instantaneous check what and the version you are using at the time"
‚úÖ **Documentation Upgrade**: Complete workflow documentation covering all improvements

I tried implementing it with procedural generation, but when I call `set_cell` or `draw_cell`, it doesn‚Äôt seem to work.

comment.body: I encountered a similar issue when attempting to implement chunk loading and unloading using TileMapDual. Whenever I directly called `draw_cell` on the main thread to update the map, it took around 16-19ms to update a 16x16 chunk, which made the physics frame very long and caused the scene to lag. I tried to address this by using multithreading, but ran into some difficulties. It seems that TileMapDual does not draw tiles correctly when not added to the scene tree, which was frustrating.

issue.title: How to document a macro that is not defined anywhere in the source code?
issue.body: I need to document a set of symbols (`#define`s) that are not declared anywhere in the source code. These symbols are meant to be provided by the user at build time when compiling our software, they are essentially build-time configuration options. I tried using the [`@def`](https://www.doxygen.nl/manual/commands.html#cmddef) command to document `#define SC_PRItime_t`, but it didn't work. ```c /** * @def SC_PRItime_t * @brief Conversion specifier to convert an object of type `time_t` to a string. * * The C99 standard does not define a format specifier for converting a `time_t` object to a string. * To work around this limitation, Users are required to define the format specifier via the * `SC_PRItime_t` symbol. */ #ifndef SC_PRItime_t #error "SC_PRItime_t macro definition missing" #endif ``` `Doxygen.conf`: ``` ENABLE_PREPROCESSING = YES MACRO_EXPANSION = YES PREDEFINED = SC_PRItime_t ``` Doxygen fails with `error: documented symbol 'define SC_PRItime_t' was not declared or defined`, I didn‚Äôt expect Doxygen to fail, since I defined the `SC_PRItime_t` macro in the `Doxygen.conf` file. For now, I‚Äôve found this dummy workaround by defining `SC_PRItime_t` in the source code just to accommodate Doxygen. ```c /** * @brief Conversion specifier to convert an object of type `time_t` to a string. * * The C99 standard does not define a format specifier for converting a `time_t` object to a string. * To work around this limitation, Users are required to define the format specifier via the * `SC_PRItime_t` symbol. */ #ifndef SC_PRItime_t #error "SC_PRItime_t macro definition missing" #define SC_PRItime_t // Just to please Doxygen #endif ``` HTML render: Is there a Doxygen command or configuration option that would allow me to achieve the same result?

comment.body:
Hello @parmi93 
simply modify your configuration a little bit:

`PREDEFINED             = DOXYGEN`

and your code:

`#ifdef DOXYGEN`
`#define SC_PRItime_t //!< Doxygen documentation`
`#endif`

Regards from Meerbusch
Thomas

commits.message:
Update .gitignore and flake.lock for improved dependency management

- Added 'result' to .gitignore to exclude build outputs.
- Updated flake.lock with new revisions and hashes for multiple dependencies to ensure compatibility and stability.
Clean up GUI modules: remove vscodium, obsidian, jetbrains-gitclient and restore original hyprland config

feat: add right panel EWW widget with modern design and system monitoring

- Add 50px wide right panel with system information display
- Implement modern CSS design with gradients, blur effects, and hover animations
- Create separate styling system for right panel (completely independent from main styles)
- Add system monitoring scripts for disk, temperature, load, and processes
- Update Hyprland configuration to reserve 50px space on the right side
- Integrate panel with EWW desktop widget system
- Add comprehensive README.md documentation
- Support Russian language and NixOS-specific configurations

feat: add current language display to right panel

- Add current-language.sh script to detect keyboard layout
- Support multiple detection methods (hyprctl, setxkbmap, localectl, env vars)
- Add current-language poll to EWW configuration
- Display current language with globe icon in right panel
- Language updates every 2 seconds
- Shows US/RU or other detected layouts

fix: resolve EWW CSS compatibility issues and improve language detection

- Fix CSS properties not supported by EWW (backdrop-filter, text-align, transform)
- Improve current-language.sh script to correctly detect Russian keyboard layout
- Use hyprctl to find main keyboard (main: yes) and get active keymap
- Script now properly returns 'RU' for Russian and 'US' for English
- Right panel now displays current language correctly
- All EWW errors resolved, panel working as intended

fix: resolve EWW CSS and configuration compatibility issues

- Fix CSS properties not supported by EWW (backdrop-filter, text-align, transform, transition, height, overflow)
- Remove unused system-info-panel widget and its styles
- Add proper CSS classes for main desktop widget (time, date, date-day)
- Add workspace styles with hover effects
- Fix workspaces initial value to prevent null indexing errors
- Fix right panel anchor for exclusive mode compatibility
- All EWW errors resolved, both desktop and right-panel working correctly

fix: position right panel correctly on the right side

- Change right panel anchor from 'center' to 'top right' for proper positioning
- Set :exclusive false to avoid EWW anchor compatibility issues
- Keep Hyprland addreserved configuration for 50px space reservation
- Panel now correctly positioned on the right side while maintaining space reservation
- Fix comment in hyprland.conf to match actual 50px reservation

refactor(eww): remove desktop widget and modernize right-panel UI

- Remove desktop widget completely (window, widget definition, CSS styles)
- Modernize right-panel design with Glassmorphism effects
- Add backdrop-filter blur effects and modern shadows
- Update color scheme from pink to universal white/transparent
- Improve typography and spacing for better readability
- Add smooth transitions and hover effects
- Update progress bars with modern color gradients
chore: commit remaining changes (eww current-language script, hyprland config)

issue.title: Fix flaky Selenium+Chrome tests
issue.body:
Since migration from HtmlUnit to Selenium+Chrome I noticed that tests more than often intermittently fail and are thus super flaky, so I tried to sort out that. It also helped to reduce total test run time by more than half.

Also fixed one IT because it expected view scoped bean behavior but used session scoped bean and was therefore not repeatable within the same session, the entire suite had to start over to reassess any flaky fail.

Also took opportunity to migrate the deprecated WebElement#getAttribute() to getDomProperty().
